# Playwright Locators
1️⃣ What is a Locator?
A locator in Playwright is a way to find and interact with elements on a web page.
It helps playwright identify buttons , text fields , links and check boxes etc .. before performing actions like:
    1. click
    2. type
    3. check
    4. select
    5. verify
👉 In simple words:
    Locator = Method used to identify an element on the webpage.
Example
-------
    page.locator("#login")
This locator finds an element with id = login

2️⃣ Why Locators are Important
Locators are the core part of Playwright automation.
They are important because they:
    1. Identify elements on the page
    2. Perform actions on elements
    3. Validate UI elements
    4. Make tests stable and reliable
Without locators , Playwright cannot interact with the UI.

3️⃣ Basic Locator Syntax
Basic syntax
------------
    page.locator("selector")

Example
-------
    page.locator("#username")
    page.locator(".login-btn")
    page.locator("text=login")

Example with actions
--------------------
    page.locator("#login").click()

4️⃣ Built-in Recommended Locators
    1️⃣ get_by_role()
    Find elements using ARIA roles.
    Example:
        page.get_by_role("button" , name = "login").click()

    Common roles:
    -------------
        Role & Example:        
        1. button -> Login button
        2. textbox -> input field
        3. link -> Hyperlink
        4. checkbox -> Checkbox
        5. radio -> Radip button

        Example:
            page.get_by_role("textbox" , name = "username")
    👉 Best practice for accessible applications

    2️⃣ get_by_text()
    Find elements using visible text
    Examples:
        page.get_by_text("Login").click()

        page.get_by_text("Submit")
    Useful when text is unique on the webpage.

    3️⃣ get_by_label()
    Used for form inputs connected with labels
    Example:
        page.get_by_label("Email")
    
    Best for :
        1. forms
        2. Input fields
    4️⃣ get_by_placeholder()
    Used for input fields that have placeholder text.
    Example:
        page.get_by_place_holder("Enter username")

    5️⃣ get_by_alt_text()
    Used for images.
    page.get_by_alt_text("Company logo")

    6️⃣ get_by_title()
    Used when elements have title attribute
    Example:
        page.get_by_title("Close")
    
    7️⃣ get_by_test_id()
    Used for test specific attributes
    Example:
        page.get_by_text_id("login-button")
    
5️⃣ Traditional Locators (CSS / XPath)
Playwright also supports CSS and XPath selectors.
    1️⃣ CSS Selectors
    Example:
        page.locator("#username")
        page.locator(".login-btn")
        page.locator("input[name = 'email']")
    
    Examples:
        page.locator("button.submit")
        page.locator("div.header")
    
    2️⃣ XPath Selectors
    Example:
        page.locator("//button[text()='Login']")
    ⚠️ XPath is supported but not recommended unless necessary.

6️⃣ Chaining Locators
Locators can be combined to find elements inside other elements.
Example HTML
------------
    <div class="card">
        <button>Buy</button>
    </div>
Locator
-------
    page.locator(".card").locator("button").click()

Meaning
-------
    1. Find ".card"
    2. Inside it find "button"

7️⃣ Filtering Locators
Playwright allows filtering elements.
Example
-------
    page.get_by_role("button").filter(has_text="Login")
Example
-------
    page.locator("div").filter(has_text="Product")

8️⃣ nth() Locator
Used when multiple elements match the same locator.
Example
------- 
    page.locator("button").nth(0)

Examples
--------
    page.locator("button").first
    page.locator("button").last

Example:
    page.locator("button").first.click()

9️⃣ Locator vs ElementHandle
Playwright recommands locator instead of ElementHandle
Locator & ElementHandle
----------------------- 
1. Auto waits -> No auto wait
2. Retry mechanism -> No retry
3. More stable -> Less stable

Example(Recommanded)
--------------------
    page.locator("#login").click()

🔟 Best Practices for Locators
Use this priority order when writing locators.
    1️⃣ get_by_role()
    2️⃣ get_by_label()
    3️⃣ get_by_placeholder()
    4️⃣ get_by_text()
    5️⃣ get_by_test_id()
    6️⃣ CSS selectors
    7️⃣ XPath (last option)

